Based on my analysis of the codebase, here's the convention for naming OTel span attributes:

## OTel Span Attribute Naming Convention

The codebase follows a **two-tier prefix strategy**:

### 1. **`emmy.*`** — Custom/emmy-specific attributes
All custom attributes are namespaced under the `emmy.` prefix, using **dot-separated snake_case**:

| Attribute | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `emmy.profile.id` | Profile identifier |
| `emmy.profile.version` | Profile version |
| `emmy.profile.hash` | Profile hash |
| `emmy.profile.variant` | Per-turn variant |
| `emmy.profile.variant_hash` | Variant hash |
| `emmy.role` | Turn role (user/assistant/system) |
| `emmy.prompt.sha256` | Prompt content hash |
| `emmy.subagent.serialized` | Subagent serialized payload |
| `emmy.subagent.final_text_chars` | Subagent output length |
| `emmy.tool.args_hash` | Tool call argument hash |
| `emmy.{event_key}` | Generic event fields from `emitEvent` (e.g., `emmy.model`, `emmy.duration_ms`) |

### 2. **`gen_ai.*`** — OTel GenAI semantic conventions
Standard [OTel GenAI semantic conventions](https://opentelemetry.io/docs/specs/semconv/gen-ai/) are used verbatim for LLM-related attributes:

| Attribute | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `gen_ai.system` | Inference system (e.g., `"vllm"`) |
| `gen_ai.request.model` | Model name |
| `gen_ai.operation.name` | Operation type (e.g., `"execute_tool"`) |
| `gen_ai.tool.name` | Tool name |
| `gen_ai.usage.input_tokens` | Input token count |
| `gen_ai.usage.output_tokens` | Output token count |
| `gen_ai.response.finish_reasons` | Finish reason array |

### Key design principles (from the code comments):

- **No ad-hoc naming** — The code explicitly avoids inventing emmy-specific names where OTel semantic conventions already exist (see `span-factory.ts` comment about "D-10 anti-pattern").
- **SpanProcessor auto-stamping** — The `EmmyProfileStampProcessor` automatically stamps `emmy.profile.*` attributes on every span at `onStart`, so callers don't need to manually add them.
- **Dot-separated snake_case** — All attribute keys use lowercase with dots as separators (e.g., `emmy.profile.variant_hash`, not `emmy.profile.variantHash`).
